We observed 2 Northern Cardinals in Vidal Wash. They were adult male and female. The male was bright red with a big crest
column47: and a red bill. The female was pale brownish-gray on its head and back. Its crest was pale red and smaller than the male''s. Its lores were black. Its throat was gray. Its wings and tail were pale red. Its breast was whitish-red and its belly was off-white.

TRIP COMMENTS: The White-winged Doves were brownish-gray with dark malars. The eyes were red surrounded by pale blue feathering. The wing coverts were white and the primaries were black. The breast was paler brown than the back. The belly back to the undertail coverts were gray. The underside of the tail was black basally and clean white distally. The tail was square-shaped. All these markings differ from the Mourning Dove''s.

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Also more Phainopeplas though they don't seem to be pairing yet. column48: here as nowhere else I have seen locally
column49: the wash ran as a result of the winter rains. The sand appears wet and saturated still.""

column47: Habitat: Desert Dry Wash Woodland--Temperature: F; Wind: mph; Cloud cover: %. Other vertebrates noted: Lepus californicus - 1; Ammospermophilus leucurus - 1.--I noted the lack of any member of the sparrow guild and ground feeders - likely because the wash had run and washed all the seeds away. I also noted that I detected higher numbers of verdins and gnatcatchers than the previous month possibly because the birds are pairing up and are more vocal and visible. Also more Phainopeplas though they don't seem to be pairing yet. Some are giving a quiet twittery song.--I noted that this wash appeared to have run water within the last month although the last rain I could remember was on 6 November
column48: one day prior to my last visit to these transects. On that day I had noted  that the wash was quite wet but did not appear to have run. That day in December I was unable to find my footprints from 7 November and
column50: those prints would still have been there. I wondered if there'd been another storm in those mountains since that we'd not noticed in Ehrenberg. Whatever the case
column51: there had to have been some water in the wash as the Lycium in this wash which put out new growth in late September
column52: died back quickly between then and November
column53: but was now putting out much more new growth than it had in September.--Plant notes: Opuntia basillaris; O. rammosissima;Pectis papposa (blooming); Encelia frutescens; Coldenia plicata and Dalea emoryi over by the cliff edge; Atriplex polycarpa (with mature seed); Datura meteloides; Encelia farinosa; Euphorbia polycarpa; Euphorbia sp.; and Asclepias subulata (blooming); Hilaria rigida was found scattered amongst the adjacent creosote flats.

column47: My description of the location: ""24.2 miles N of junction Hwy 95 and Hobsonway Rd."" My description of the site itself. ""Read Parker 31
column51: PI Robert Ohmart). All 3 transects are screwbean mesquite (Prosopis pubescens). A few cottonwoods grow along 7A and 7B and there is a small copse of screwbean amongst the Pluchea at the end of Parker 31. This is where the cuckoo was heard. 7A and 7B are differentiated because their respective structure types differ - generally between 15' and 20' on A but 15' or lower on B. They all have some salt cedar (Tamarix) although not much on Parker 31. All have patches of Pluchea as well.... An absolutely beautiful day today. Clear and partly cloudy.""--Habitat: Screwbean Mesquite.--Temperature: 65-->85F; Wind: 0-5 mph; Cloud cover: 50-->30%. Other vertebrates noted: Sceloporus magister - 2; Neotoma albigula - 1 nest.

column48: 1977 rains but doesn't appear to have done so extensively. No significant visible damage. This was the only type V desert wash transect due to the size of the taller trees in the wash - the vegetation is very sparse compared to the type VI east side washes. Lycium dormant here (in contrast to the leafed out and flowering plants in the east side washes). Some of the smoke trees had put out a few blossoms that were just opening and Stephanomeria also in bloom.--Ash-throated Flycatchers have vacated these washes now.

column48: 1977 rains but doesn't appear to have done so extensively. No significant visible damage. This was the only type V desert wash transect due to the size of the taller trees in the wash - the vegetation is very sparse compared to the type VI east side washes. Lycium dormant here (in contrast to the leafed out and flowering plants in the east side washes). The White-winged Doves were brownish-gray with dark malars. The eyes were red surrounded by pale blue feathering. The wing coverts were white and the primaries were black. The breast was paler brown than the back. The belly back to the undertail coverts were gray. The underside of the tail was black basally and clean white distally. The tail was square-shaped. All these markings differ from the Mourning Dove''s.

column46: but not quite as I dried as I feared
column47: given the condition of McCoy and the Upper Chemehuevi.  Creosote leaves mostly brown with some green in them.  Nothing flowering save blue palo verdes
column48: but quite a few of those were in flower
column49: some of them nearly totally in flower. Lower than expected Verdin numbers.  A handful of Phainopeplas
column50: none of them nesting/territorial.  I flushed a large
column51: silver bat (silver hoary?) - I didn't see it and nearly walked into it; it would have been an excellent picture to catch it roosting.  The plant condition reminds me most of Milpitas.  Wetter than McCoy
column53: not as wet as Salt Creek 1.  ----The powerline people destroyed several old-growth palo verdes and ironwoods about 60m west of point 38.  Unbelievably wrong-headed
column54: do they think these trees are saplings?  Even the tallest ones do not come within 10m of the lines
column55: and they chopped them all.  To top it off
column56: they have left all the wood and branches in piles - nothing can grow in and it is a fire threat.  Sad and silly.----Zero hummingbirds.  feels weird on the wash where I found the project's first ANHU nest in 2004 and have found several COHU nests.

column46: Unplanned stop at lagoon with numerous birds.

Tom Benson and I spent an extended period of time along the west side of an ephemeral pond in search of a Little Blue Heron that David Vander Pluym had found earlier in the day.  I parked myself along the roadside about halfway up the west side of the pond at a location form which I could scan most of the pond from one location.  While I scoped the pond
column47: Tom worked both north and south along the road to find additional vantage points in search of the heron.  The pond was about 100 meters across and approximately 200 meters long
column48: with extensive dead vegetation (likely tamarisk trees) to the south that created the appearance of a wooded swamp
column49: but there were also scattered stands of cattails along the shoreline mixed with scrubby tamarisk shrubs of various sizes.  The result of the densely vegetated borders to the pond was that many of the birds seen were visible only intermittently between long periods of obscurity.  Although we could scan much of the pond from our positions
column50: our coverage for land birds in particular was quite limited and representing primarily what I could hear from my position.  It was mostly clear
column51: but with a <5% cover of mid-level and high clouds along the horizons to the northeast and southwest
column52: a mild (5+ knot) breeze from the southwest
column53: and temperatures that ranged 92-93 F (based on the thermometer in my vehicle).  2:55-3:25 pm
column54: and again

column46: Given recent reports of Ridgway's Rails at the cattail-lined pond along the road at Bluewater
column47: I stood at a good vantage point and scanned the edges of this pond and listened for any rails that may happened to vocalize.  Unfortunately
column48: despite the presence of a couple of young Least Bitterns and at least three family groups of Green Herons
column49: the only rail I managed to find was a Common Gallinule.  I heard and saw incidentally a number of land birds singing and calling from the edges of the pond and the adjacent scrub
column50: but my concentration was along the edge of the pond.  It was clear
column52: and 72 F on my arrival (based on the thermometer in my vehicle).  5:55-6:40 am.

column46: but during our brief stop we did our best to scan from the roadside the birds that were concentrated mostly on the far side of the lake.  Given the brevity and late timing of our visit
column47: this list is best considered an incomplete one that concentrated on the birds in and along the edges of the pond
column48: with land birds mostly heard incidentally. -- It was clear
column50: and 65 F on our arrival (based on the thermometer in my vehicle).  4:40-4:50 pm.

I returned to the River Lodge Resort this morning hoping for better success with cowbirds
column46: but even though there were in general more birds than I saw the previous day
column47: none of them were cowbirds.  I again carefully walked the golf course
column48: but today I also walked around the northern part of the campground and along the river
column49: and before leaving the site I drove a loop around the entire resort
column50: which was again unproductive.  My efforts were concentrated around the lawns and scattered trees on the golf course
column51: b I also checked the trees in the northern part of the trailer park
column54: and shoreline bordering the river.  It was clear
column56: and with temperatures increasing from 80 F to 96 F during my morning visit.  6:55-8:40 am.----Wild Burro - 10;--Desert Cottontail - 3.

TRIP COMMENTS: I spent the middle part of the day checking the River Lodge Resort in search of Bronzed Cowbirds
column46: which had been found reliably at this location in recent years.  Given that the cowbirds had been found most easily on the golf course
column47: I walked a circuit of almost the entire course beginning at the marked and working an essentially clockwise loop around the perimeter checking the lawns and adjacent trees
column48: most of which were medium-sized mesquites. but also with with fan palms along the roads.  Following a period spent in the market cooling off
column49: I slowly drove a loop throughout the site looking for birds on the ground and obvious birds in the cottonwoods and other trees scattered about the site.  I found a reasonable selection of the expected species
column50: including at least two family groups of Lucy's Warblers and a family of roadrunners
column51: yet I was unable to locate any cowbirds.  It was clear
column52: with a mild (increasing to 5 knots) breeze from the south
column53: and temperatures that increased from 104 F on my arrival to 111 F on my early-afternoon departure (based on the thermometer in my vehicle).  10:45 am - 1:00 pm.

TRIP COMMENTS: Birding with John Luther. Around dusk last night we finally arrived at the Colorado River. We were hoping to find the Sandhill Cranes that originally had been reported by Tom Benson & Brad Singer. So after arriving in the small town of Big River
column46: we drove over to the area close to the RV park that had been mentioned in their report. We stopped at the corner of Chippewa Dr & Capistrano to figure out where the actually area was when we looked below us and found ~ 80 SANDHILL CRANES! Mixed in with them were also 2 SNOW GEESE & 3 HOODED MERGANSERS. They all seem to be hanging out in a shallow pond easily seen from the road.

column47: has a very interesting appearance. Restoration folks have taken large blocks of farmland
column48: evidently with an irrigation scheme in place and planted these areas with trees and shrubs to bring back the riparian ecosystem. However
column50: the landscape in most of these appears a monoculture of even-aged Fremont Cottonwoods
column51: and completely lacks structural heterogeneity with openings or with a shrub or herb layer. Searching the web
column52: I see no  concern by restoration ecologists or others that the efforts here perhaps warrant a different approach to more closely approximate a functioning riparian ecosystem. The cottonwood blocks may be focused on bringing back Yellow-billed Cuckoos
column54: which appears to be occurring. The cottonwood tracts caught my attention foremost
column55: the other blocks of habitat appear more natural
column56: such as areas of Mesquite thickets near the parking area and at the north end of the site. In those areas
column58: areas of rough fields appear more natural
column59: at least based on structural characteristics. In deference to restoration ecologists
column60: perhaps they are planning to introduce disturbance into the landscapes here (to create openings) and prompt growth of elements that will promote structural diversity.
